{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:52:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:52:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17477"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56206"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5458"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23789"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman visits her general practitioner for advice about preventing breast cancer. She has no personal or family history of breast cancer but is concerned about her risk as she gets older.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes primary prevention for breast cancer in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular mammogram screening","Breast self-examination training","Lifestyle modifications to reduce risk factors","Genetic testing for BRCA mutations","Early treatment of suspicious lesions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Elifestyle modifications to reduce risk factors\u003C/strong\u003E. Primary prevention involves actions taken before disease occurs, such as maintaining healthy body weight, regular exercise, limiting alcohol intake, and avoiding hormone replacement therapy when possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular mammogram screening\u003C/strong\u003E is secondary prevention as it aims to detect existing disease early\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast self-examination training\u003C/strong\u003E is also secondary prevention as it focuses on early detection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing for BRCA mutations\u003C/strong\u003E is a screening tool that would be more appropriate for those with family history\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly treatment of suspicious lesions\u003C/strong\u003E represents secondary prevention as it involves treating early disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary prevention focuses on preventing disease before it occurs through risk factor modification. Secondary and tertiary prevention deal with early detection and management of established disease respectively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary prevention aims to prevent disease before it occurs through measures like vaccination and health education.","Secondary prevention focuses on early detection and intervention of disease before symptoms develop.","Tertiary prevention aims to reduce the impact of established disease through rehabilitation and preventing complications."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Sim MG, Khong E. Prevention--building on routine clinical practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2006;35(1-2):12-15.","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Guidelines for preventive activities in general practice. 9th edn, updated. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP, 2018. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/FSDEDEV/media/documents/Clinical%20Resources/Guidelines/Red%20Book/Guidelines-for-preventive-activities-in-general-practice.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56206"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56206"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:37:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:38:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":n